Captive reared larvae became increasingly active a few days prior to pupation, possibly in search of a suitable pupation site. During morning field collections, larvae were sometimes found crawling on the surface of the marginal substrate. Captive individuals became increasingly active during the morning from 0900–1100hrs. In the field, mature larvae were often found beside a rock that was much larger than the larva, sometimes partially buried in the contiguous sandy substrata (
Fig. 52
).
